<section id="section-6">
<title> Centripetal acceleration </title>
<example id="example-31b">
<para id="element-31b"><term>Problem : </term> Find the centripetal acceleration (in 
<m:math>
<m:mspace width="2pt"/>
<m:mi> km </m:mi>
<m:mo> / </m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> hr </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
</m:math>
) at a point on the equator of the earth (consider earth as a sphere of radius = 6400 km).
</para>
<para id="element-33"><term>Solution : </term>
The centripetal acceleration in terms of angular speed is given by :
</para>
<para id="element-34">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi> a </m:mi>
<m:mo> = </m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> ω </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
<m:mi> r </m:mi>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-35">
Now, angular speed, in terms of time period is :
</para>
<para id="element-36">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi> ω </m:mi>
<m:mo> = </m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
<m:mi> π </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
<m:mi> T </m:mi>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-37">
Combining two equations, we have :
</para>
<para id="element-38">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi> a </m:mi>
<m:mo> = </m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mn> 4 </m:mn>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> π </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
<m:mi> r </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> T </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-39"><m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mo> ⇒ </m:mo> 
<m:mi> a </m:mi>
<m:mo> = </m:mo>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mn> 4 </m:mn>
<m:mo> x </m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mrow>
<m:mo> ( </m:mo>
<m:mn> 3.14 </m:mn>
<m:mo> ) </m:mo>
</m:mrow>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
<m:mo> x </m:mo>
